node.text:
The Netherlands’ famous tulip wonderland🌷😍 Would you visit this beautiful floral field?

Tulips have a long and rich cultural history in The Netherlands. They are the country’s national flowers and have been increasingly popular since the 17th century. The Netherlands is also home to Keukenhof, the largest flower garden in the world..and if you’d like to witness these stunning flowers in person, we recommend planning a trip between blooming season, which starts late March and ends mid May! 💐

📍 The Netherlands

🇳🇱 #discoverNetherlands

A beach made of dreams 💚 Can you guess what gives Russia’s Kaleidoscope Beach its jewel-like pebbles?

While it might seem like a natural wonder, the beach was actually formed with years of unwanted bottle waste that has been smoothed, buffed and polished by erosion. This amazing transformation has made the Ussuri Bay one of the world’s most unique – and colourful – beaches ever. ✨ 

Insider tip: The Ussuri Bay is also worth visiting during winter, when the shore glistens even more under the frosty light.

📍Ussuri Bay, Russia 

🇷🇺 #discoverRussia

Can’t get enough of this amazing bioluminescent glow 🤩

Did you know that bioluminescence (the process that adds an electric blue colour to coasts) is quite rare to find? But if you’re looking to experience this magic in person and swim in sparkling blue waters, Jervis Bay in Australia might be the perfect pick for you. 🌊

Insider tip: Even if you don’t spot bioluminescence on the shores, Jervis Bay will still take your breath away with its pearl-white sand, sheltered surroundings and rich marine life. 🐬

📍Jervis Bay, Australia

🇦🇺 #discoverAustralia with @jordan_robins

The most magical surf experience 🌊✨ Would you surf on the electric blue coasts of Venice Beach?

This is the perfect example of just how amazing nature can be. Over the past few years, people have spotted the appearance of bioluminescence on the coasts of California, which lend it this sparkling blue shine. Bioluminescence is a chemical reaction that produces light energy in the body of the organism – think fireflies, or in this case, marine algae. 

📍Venice Beach, California, United States

🇺🇸 #discoverUnitedStates with @louiscole

Meet Meayunan, a traditional swing game of Tenganan, Bali 😍

Traditions have been handed down from generation to generation in Tenganan Village, including this swing game. This tradition is only played once every year, but it’s not just for entertainment – the swing’s spinning symbolises life’s cycle and the way it continues to swing up and down.

Insider tip: If you’d like to witness Meayunan, visit Tenganan Village during the Usabha Sambah ritual, which is held in the fifth month of the village’s calendar.

📍Tenganan, Bali, Indonesia

🇮🇩 #discoverIndonesia with @juni_newman

node.text:
An ice cave glowing like amber from the golden rays of a setting sun. ✨

“The golden rays of the sunset entered the cave at just the right angle to light up this section of ice, making it look like amber. It was so a bright orange stripe running along the wall of the ice cave. Definitely one of the more unique things I have seen” says @sarah.bethea

We are also obsessed with the sunrays on this cave…and if you’re planning to go to Iceland, make sure to visit the country’s stunning ice caves ❄️

Insider tip: While in Iceland, why not organise a whale watching tour or a trip to the beautiful waterfalls and mysterious lakes of Iceland? 🐋

📍 Iceland

🇮🇸 #discoverIceland with @sarah.bethea
